1
00:02:13,634 --> 00:02:15,159
Shouldn't they be up by now?

2
00:02:15,235 --> 00:02:16,703
I'm sure they're fine.

3
00:02:16,903 --> 00:02:18,929
They're gonna run out of air.

4
00:02:19,039 --> 00:02:20,268
I'm happy to kill my daughter,

5
00:02:20,340 --> 00:02:22,434
but I'd feel a little awkward
about killing your son.

6
00:02:22,542 --> 00:02:25,569
They're spending
time together, it's good.

7
00:02:25,912 --> 00:02:28,313
We're a family now.
They need to bond.

8
00:02:28,415 --> 00:02:32,614
Yeah. Well, they can
bond with full air intake.

9
00:02:36,123 --> 00:02:38,092
Julie, surface now!

10
00:02:38,358 --> 00:02:40,088
Help! Shark!

11
00:02:45,632 --> 00:02:47,032
Please don't scare me like that.

12
00:02:47,100 --> 00:02:49,262
What? You said we should bond.

13
00:02:49,770 --> 00:02:50,863
Look what I found!

14
00:02:51,838 --> 00:02:54,808
You're not supposed to
take anything off the wreck.

15
00:03:04,518 --> 00:03:06,612
How cool is this?

16
00:03:09,356 --> 00:03:11,791
They kind of look like feathers.

17
00:03:11,858 --> 00:03:12,951
Can I see?

18
00:03:14,361 --> 00:03:15,385
Ow!

19
00:03:15,462 --> 00:03:16,725
Julie!

20
00:03:18,198 --> 00:03:20,224
Get her a towel.

21
00:03:20,467 --> 00:03:22,333
What was in that jar?

22
00:04:00,440 --> 00:04:01,931
Why aren't you
guys in my office?

23
00:04:02,042 --> 00:04:03,510
Why are you in the building?

24
00:04:03,577 --> 00:04:04,909
It's 8:00 in the morning.

25
00:04:05,011 --> 00:04:06,070
Where's Chase?

26
00:04:06,179 --> 00:04:08,512
He's not here because
it's 8:00 in the morning.

27
00:04:08,582 --> 00:04:13,577
Sixteen-year-old girl, high
fever, vomiting, bloodshot eyes.

28
00:04:13,687 --> 00:04:16,555
Wow, the case of
the really bad flu.

29
00:04:16,623 --> 00:04:18,785
Hmm. Let me see. Did
I leave anything out?

30
00:04:18,892 --> 00:04:21,123
Oh, yeah. The smallpox.

31
00:04:23,897 --> 00:04:26,366
Smallpox was eradicated
over 30 years ago.

32
00:04:26,433 --> 00:04:28,095
So were Hush Puppies.
Did you check out

33
00:04:28,168 --> 00:04:29,761
your local hipster
coffee shop lately?

34
00:04:29,870 --> 00:04:33,204
Smallpox doesn't exist outside
of P4 labs and bio weapon plants.

35
00:04:33,273 --> 00:04:34,434
She was in Bermuda...

36
00:04:34,541 --> 00:04:36,100
Where she was scuba-diving

37
00:04:36,176 --> 00:04:37,906
on the wreck of
a Dutch slave ship

38
00:04:37,978 --> 00:04:39,776
that had been intentionally sunk

39
00:04:39,880 --> 00:04:42,111
because an epidemic of
smallpox had broken out onboard.

40
00:04:42,215 --> 00:04:44,081
Was the ship sunk in water?

41
00:04:44,151 --> 00:04:46,062
Because viruses can't
survive contact with water.

42
00:04:46,086 --> 00:04:48,749
And if the virus had been kept
on the outside of an airtight jar,

43
00:04:48,822 --> 00:04:49,915
that might be an issue.

44
00:04:50,290 --> 00:04:52,486
The jar held
old-school inoculations.

45
00:04:52,559 --> 00:04:54,637
They kept the scabs
of the infected people.

46
00:04:54,661 --> 00:04:56,721
The virus can't survive
over 200 years...

47
00:04:56,830 --> 00:04:57,957
You have.

48
00:04:59,332 --> 00:05:02,393
Thanks for calling back.
Listen, I'm a screenwriter.

49
00:05:02,469 --> 00:05:06,338
And is it theoretically
possible for smallpox

50
00:05:06,439 --> 00:05:07,805
to survive for more
than 200 years

51
00:05:07,874 --> 00:05:10,935
underwater in a
sealed glass jar?

52
00:05:11,011 --> 00:05:13,446
<i>Well, theoretically, yes, but...</i>

53
00:05:13,513 --> 00:05:14,640
Thank you.

54
00:05:15,015 --> 00:05:18,179
So who do we believe,
the CDC or Dr. 90210?

55
00:05:18,451 --> 00:05:22,286
Isolate, get the baseline blood
draws for smallpox antibodies,

56
00:05:22,355 --> 00:05:24,256
then vaccinate
the entire family.

57
00:05:24,324 --> 00:05:26,759
We should test for the
21st century suspects.

58
00:05:26,827 --> 00:05:28,455
Varicella, measles...

59
00:05:28,528 --> 00:05:29,672
You're free to perform whatever

60
00:05:29,696 --> 00:05:31,289
unnecessary tests
you want, Foreman.

61
00:05:31,364 --> 00:05:33,162
Slavery was abolished years ago.

62
00:05:46,613 --> 00:05:49,276
Why the hell do you guys
have us quarantined in here?

63
00:05:49,349 --> 00:05:51,215
We're just taking
every precaution.

64
00:05:51,318 --> 00:05:52,547
Against what?

65
00:05:53,820 --> 00:05:55,311
What do you think I have?

66
00:05:55,388 --> 00:05:57,289
One possibility is tetanus

67
00:05:57,357 --> 00:05:59,986
from the glass jar
that sliced your hand.

68
00:06:00,060 --> 00:06:03,224
I remember tetanus shots. That
does not look like tetanus shots.

69
00:06:03,330 --> 00:06:04,855
It's really not
worth going into,

70
00:06:04,931 --> 00:06:06,524
because the odds
are astronomical.

71
00:06:08,802 --> 00:06:10,361
Tell me.

72
00:06:12,439 --> 00:06:14,408
Again, it's... Smallpox.

73
00:06:16,176 --> 00:06:17,439
Smallpox?

74
00:06:19,346 --> 00:06:21,146
Vaccine will protect
you if you don't have it,

75
00:06:21,214 --> 00:06:23,342
and lessen the severity
if you already do.

76
00:06:24,684 --> 00:06:28,712
But it's a billion-to-one, so we
don't want you to panic or anything.

77
00:06:29,022 --> 00:06:31,958
How do I not panic
with that information?

78
00:06:39,866 --> 00:06:43,735
Idiot in exam room one needs
anti-diarrheals and a dictionary.

79
00:06:43,803 --> 00:06:45,738
You're not scheduled
for clinic duty now.

80
00:06:45,805 --> 00:06:48,775
I had some free time.
I owed four hours...

81
00:06:48,975 --> 00:06:50,773
Don't you have a case? Yeah.

82
00:06:50,877 --> 00:06:52,209
Then don't worry about it.

83
00:06:53,613 --> 00:06:55,047
Are you a Stepford doctor?

84
00:06:55,115 --> 00:06:57,311
If you're busy, you don't
need to be down here.

85
00:06:58,051 --> 00:06:59,212
You're serious.

86
00:06:59,286 --> 00:07:01,482
Yep. Get out of here.

87
00:07:05,625 --> 00:07:06,752
I can't.

88
00:07:06,960 --> 00:07:09,054
I forgot her stuffed
animal at home.

89
00:07:09,129 --> 00:07:12,099
It's been with her through
all the chemo sessions so far.

90
00:07:12,165 --> 00:07:13,929
I need Lamby.

91
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:15,400
She doesn't want
me to do it alone.

92
00:07:16,069 --> 00:07:18,038
Honey, there's no other way.

93
00:07:18,104 --> 00:07:19,800
You're just gonna
have to be brave, okay?

94
00:07:20,073 --> 00:07:22,008
What if I get
someone to sit with her

95
00:07:22,075 --> 00:07:24,067
while you run home
and get Lamby?

96
00:07:25,979 --> 00:07:31,111
I'll get a nurse. Then I have
to deal with a very sick man.

97
00:07:40,260 --> 00:07:42,024
I think she knows.

98
00:07:42,829 --> 00:07:44,661
Who is she, and
what does she know?

99
00:07:44,798 --> 00:07:48,030
Cuddy and that
I faked a lab test

100
00:07:48,101 --> 00:07:49,661
and lied to her to
save my last patient.

101
00:07:49,703 --> 00:07:50,762
What did she do?

102
00:07:50,837 --> 00:07:54,239
She let me out of clinic
duty because I had a case.

103
00:07:54,741 --> 00:07:56,004
She's never done that.

104
00:07:56,076 --> 00:07:57,874
She's also probably
never ordered

105
00:07:57,944 --> 00:07:59,879
the pasta special
in the cafeteria.

106
00:07:59,980 --> 00:08:02,677
Would that also have some special
paranoid message to send you?

107
00:08:02,749 --> 00:08:04,547
I am not imagining this.

108
00:08:04,651 --> 00:08:07,746
It's an aberration in the
way that she treats me.

109
00:08:07,854 --> 00:08:09,031
How do I find out what it means?

110
00:08:09,055 --> 00:08:10,580
You don't. If she doesn't know,

111
00:08:10,690 --> 00:08:12,702
all you're gonna do by sniffing
around is make her suspicious.

112
00:08:12,726 --> 00:08:14,991
If she does know, you'll
find out soon enough.

113
00:08:15,061 --> 00:08:16,927
What if I die of curiosity
in the meantime?

114
00:08:17,030 --> 00:08:19,192
You were an idiot for
lying to her in the first place.

115
00:08:19,265 --> 00:08:21,063
Don't be more of an idiot now.

116
00:08:21,167 --> 00:08:24,433
Say nothing. To no
one. About anything.

117
00:08:24,537 --> 00:08:25,835
That includes me.

118
00:08:33,580 --> 00:08:34,946
It's not smallpox.

119
00:08:35,081 --> 00:08:38,347
Blood work suggests some other
infection. White count is way down.

120
00:08:40,253 --> 00:08:42,552
Masters, you got a boyfriend?

121
00:08:42,956 --> 00:08:44,356
That's none of your business.

122
00:08:44,557 --> 00:08:46,048
Probably just a dry spell.

123
00:08:46,226 --> 00:08:50,095
House, you do realize
we just ruled out smallpox?

124
00:08:50,230 --> 00:08:53,723
Would you ever be extra
nice to a theoretical boyfriend

125
00:08:53,967 --> 00:08:55,367
if you were really mad at him?

126
00:08:56,536 --> 00:08:59,768
I guess the only reason I would
be extra nice is because I'm angry,

127
00:08:59,873 --> 00:09:01,102
and I just want him to go away

128
00:09:01,174 --> 00:09:02,774
so I don't have to
deal with him anymore.

129
00:09:03,810 --> 00:09:05,802
You passive-aggressive bitch.

130
00:09:05,945 --> 00:09:07,106
You just asked me...

131
00:09:07,180 --> 00:09:08,978
What about Foreman's
unnecessary tests?

132
00:09:09,082 --> 00:09:10,607
Negative for
varicella and measles.

133
00:09:10,683 --> 00:09:12,379
So all of our ideas
are off the table.

134
00:09:12,819 --> 00:09:14,447
I'm putting mine back on.

135
00:09:14,654 --> 00:09:16,122
Patient's a diver.

136
00:09:16,256 --> 00:09:18,176
Under increased pressure,
everything in the blood

137
00:09:18,224 --> 00:09:20,159
gets scared, panics,
runs and hides.

138
00:09:20,260 --> 00:09:21,888
Antibodies could
be in the joints.

139
00:09:21,961 --> 00:09:23,725
Tap her knee, ankle, shoulder,

140
00:09:23,930 --> 00:09:27,094
and any other joint in
her smallpox-ridden body.

141
00:09:27,167 --> 00:09:28,328
Good talk.

142
00:09:43,817 --> 00:09:44,978
You know.

143
00:09:45,685 --> 00:09:46,812
Of course I know.

144
00:09:47,087 --> 00:09:48,851
Oh, thank God.

145
00:09:49,923 --> 00:09:51,824
I thought I was
just being paranoid.

146
00:09:52,258 --> 00:09:53,692
Why didn't you say something?

147
00:09:53,793 --> 00:09:56,456
'Cause I wanted you to
come to me and apologize.

148
00:09:56,529 --> 00:09:58,623
I can't apologize if I
haven't done anything wrong.

149
00:10:00,033 --> 00:10:01,092
You lied to my face.

150
00:10:01,267 --> 00:10:04,294
To do my job. To
save the patient's life.

151
00:10:04,671 --> 00:10:08,665
Look, I don't wanna go all <i>Godfather</i>
on you, but this was business.

152
00:10:08,775 --> 00:10:10,641
I wouldn't lie to you
about something personal.

153
00:10:10,710 --> 00:10:13,874
You don't get to lie
to me about anything.

154
00:10:14,314 --> 00:10:16,146
I can't compartmentalize
my life like that.

155
00:10:16,216 --> 00:10:18,981
Well, maybe you should
practice, 'cause it comes in handy.

156
00:10:26,526 --> 00:10:27,789
I think you should go.

157
00:10:39,739 --> 00:10:40,832
Ow.

158
00:10:40,907 --> 00:10:42,398
Sorry.

159
00:10:43,009 --> 00:10:45,342
I have to get the
needle behind the bone.

160
00:10:45,411 --> 00:10:47,642
I'm running out of bones.

161
00:10:47,714 --> 00:10:49,234
If this is a waste
of time... Last one.

162
00:10:50,517 --> 00:10:52,850
We just have to be...

163
00:10:54,154 --> 00:10:55,213
What?

164
00:10:56,890 --> 00:10:58,358
What is it?

165
00:11:00,226 --> 00:11:03,526
I'm sorry. I have
to call the CDC.

166
00:11:03,930 --> 00:11:05,899
I think you do have smallpox.

167
00:11:15,675 --> 00:11:17,200
Am I gonna die?

168
00:11:17,277 --> 00:11:19,041
I mean, this is what terrorists

169
00:11:19,112 --> 00:11:20,842
want to use to kill
everyone, right?

170
00:11:20,914 --> 00:11:21,938
Like, there's no cure.

171
00:11:22,048 --> 00:11:24,779
There are treatments.
We can give you cidofovir...

172
00:11:24,884 --> 00:11:26,684
I don't think you care
about the drugs' names.

173
00:11:26,753 --> 00:11:29,052
Bottom line, it's 30% fatal.

174
00:11:29,122 --> 00:11:31,167
Which means your chances of
being okay are about the same

175
00:11:31,191 --> 00:11:34,525
as a basketball player's
chance of hitting a free throw.

176
00:11:34,694 --> 00:11:38,461
Unless she finds dark,
purplish skin blotches.

177
00:11:39,199 --> 00:11:41,031
What would purple blotches mean?

178
00:11:41,134 --> 00:11:42,932
Hemorrhagic-type smallpox.

179
00:11:43,102 --> 00:11:46,368
In which case, her chances are
more like Shaq hitting a free throw.

180
00:11:46,706 --> 00:11:49,437
Well, no purple skin,
but take a look at this.

181
00:11:50,543 --> 00:11:51,602
What is it?

182
00:11:51,744 --> 00:11:54,145
There's a rash under
your daughter's arm.

183
00:11:55,281 --> 00:11:57,045
What, like, more of
those gross bumps?

184
00:11:59,953 --> 00:12:02,252
No. It's just a regular rash.

185
00:12:02,388 --> 00:12:04,186
What does that mean?

186
00:12:05,758 --> 00:12:07,556
It means it's not smallpox.

187
00:12:15,535 --> 00:12:17,731
Are you saying you
see House's side?

188
00:12:17,804 --> 00:12:21,468
It's not even a side, it's
a fictional construction.

189
00:12:21,574 --> 00:12:23,372
She's expecting
House not to lie?

190
00:12:23,443 --> 00:12:24,843
If she's using the relationship

191
00:12:24,911 --> 00:12:26,641
as a rationale to try
to change things...

192
00:12:26,746 --> 00:12:29,580
Wait, wait. Are you saying it's
okay for us to lie to each other?

193
00:12:29,649 --> 00:12:32,118
No. We have a different
relationship. I think a better one.

194
00:12:32,218 --> 00:12:34,818
Lying was never part
of it. Theirs is built on it.

195
00:12:35,989 --> 00:12:37,252
I'm sorry. I have to go.

196
00:12:37,323 --> 00:12:39,622
Oh, come on. I have to
leave in, like, five minutes.

197
00:12:39,726 --> 00:12:41,285
Can't it wait?
There's a little girl.

198
00:12:41,394 --> 00:12:42,771
The nurse watching
her got called away.

199
00:12:42,795 --> 00:12:46,095
It's a long story,
but I've gotta babysit.

200
00:12:46,466 --> 00:12:47,593
I'll see you tonight.

201
00:12:48,401 --> 00:12:50,529
<i>Attention. Effective
immediately,</i>

202
00:12:50,603 --> 00:12:52,970
<i>all hospital entrances
and exits will be restricted</i>

203
00:12:53,072 --> 00:12:54,335
<i>until further notice.</i>

204
00:12:54,440 --> 00:12:55,920
<i>Center for Disease
Control has ordered</i>

205
00:12:55,975 --> 00:12:57,615
<i>Princeton-Plainsboro
Hospital locked down.</i>

206
00:12:57,944 --> 00:12:59,936
Well, I guess I can stay.

207
00:13:07,153 --> 00:13:09,019
Please, step out of the room.

208
00:13:12,659 --> 00:13:16,357
I'm Dr. Broda, Head of
Infection Control, CDC.

209
00:13:16,829 --> 00:13:18,764
And your protective
suits are not adequate.

210
00:13:18,831 --> 00:13:20,629
Turns out they don't have to be.

211
00:13:20,700 --> 00:13:22,430
Rash under the arm
means it's not smallpox.

212
00:13:22,669 --> 00:13:24,103
False alarm.

213
00:13:24,370 --> 00:13:26,965
Sorry, hope the
traffic wasn't too bad.

214
00:13:27,040 --> 00:13:28,633
Rash is consistent
with smallpox.

215
00:13:28,708 --> 00:13:30,438
Not if it presents
after pustules.

216
00:13:30,510 --> 00:13:31,787
She's probably just allergic

217
00:13:31,811 --> 00:13:33,336
to the bed sheets
or the hospital gown.

218
00:13:33,446 --> 00:13:34,686
Or you simply didn't notice it.

219
00:13:34,714 --> 00:13:37,707
We're gonna airlift blood
and tissue samples to Atlanta.

220
00:13:37,817 --> 00:13:39,718
We'll have the DNA
results in 18 hours.

221
00:13:40,119 --> 00:13:43,521
In the meantime, please,
step out of the room.

222
00:13:43,823 --> 00:13:46,054
You brought the plane? Cool.

223
00:13:49,962 --> 00:13:52,989
When we left, Julie's
fever had climbed over 103.

224
00:13:53,066 --> 00:13:55,377
It's not smallpox, she's not
dying, and it's not our case.

225
00:13:55,401 --> 00:13:57,165
Need any other
reasons to forget it?

226
00:13:57,236 --> 00:13:59,569
You know how you can tell
there's nothing to be done?

227
00:13:59,672 --> 00:14:00,696
Chase showed up.

228
00:14:00,807 --> 00:14:01,866
I was here at 9:00.

229
00:14:02,008 --> 00:14:04,219
So you guys just want to do
nothing for the next 18 hours

230
00:14:04,243 --> 00:14:06,041
until they tell us
it's not smallpox?

231
00:14:06,245 --> 00:14:07,975
Can't we spend
the time discussing

232
00:14:08,047 --> 00:14:11,347
what looks like smallpox
but isn't smallpox?

233
00:14:11,417 --> 00:14:12,646
Molluscum contagiosum.

234
00:14:12,719 --> 00:14:14,479
You have to compare
lesions to differentiate.

235
00:14:14,520 --> 00:14:17,388
But we don't have access to
the patient or any new information.

236
00:14:17,523 --> 00:14:20,357
We do have access
to the other patients.

237
00:14:20,426 --> 00:14:23,021
The ones who died of
the same thing in 1793.

238
00:14:23,262 --> 00:14:26,255
The captain's log from
the <i>Sotos Ooslerzoon.</i>

239
00:14:26,532 --> 00:14:29,866
Maritime Museum in Bermuda
graciously sent over a PDF.

240
00:14:29,936 --> 00:14:31,165
Problem solved.

241
00:14:32,004 --> 00:14:34,064
I assume at least one of
you speaks fluent Dutch.

242
00:14:35,842 --> 00:14:37,953
It's the middle of the
night in the Netherlands.

243
00:14:37,977 --> 00:14:39,036
Nobody's working.

244
00:14:39,212 --> 00:14:41,545
Oh, you can always find someone.

245
00:14:41,914 --> 00:14:44,349
<i>Oh, yes. My name is Geerte.</i>

246
00:14:44,584 --> 00:14:47,577
<i>Are you handsome
sexiest American man?</i>

247
00:14:48,721 --> 00:14:49,950
Well, you know, some people...

248
00:14:51,190 --> 00:14:53,591
I would say that I am, yeah.

249
00:14:53,693 --> 00:14:55,355
I want you to translate
something for me.

